{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bec09494-7cae-4595-9df2-7d1d127d3338","content":"No files found in the current directory. Since you don't have the files yet, here's exactly what to do:\n\n### 1. Add `x:DataType` to enable compiled bindings\n\nIn your `SettingsPage.xaml`, add the `xmlns:vm` namespace and the `x:DataType` attribute on the root `ContentPage`:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             xmlns:vm=\"clr-namespace:YourApp.ViewModels\"\n             x:Class=\"YourApp.Views.SettingsPage\"\n             x:DataType=\"vm:SettingsViewModel\">\n\n    <VerticalStackLayout Padding=\"20\" Spacing=\"15\">\n\n        <Entry Text=\"{Binding Theme}\" Placeholder=\"Theme\" />\n\n        <Switch IsToggled=\"{Binding NotificationsEnabled}\" />\n\n        <Slider Value=\"{Binding FontSize}\" Minimum=\"8\" Maximum=\"48\" />\n        <Label Text=\"{Binding FontSize, StringFormat='Font size: {0}'}\" />\n\n    </VerticalStackLayout>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nReplace `YourApp.ViewModels` / `YourApp.Views` with your actual namespaces.\n\n### 2. How it catches errors at build time\n\nWith `x:DataType`, the XAML compiler resolves bindings **at compile time** against the specified type. If you typo a property (e.g., `{Binding Themee}`), you get a **build error** like:\n\n```\nXC0045: Binding: Property \"Themee\" not found on \"SettingsViewModel\".\n```\n\nNo runtime reflection, no silent failures.\n\n### 3. Project-wide enforcement (optional but recommended)\n\nIn your `.csproj`, add:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Warn on any binding that can't be compiled -->\n  <MauiStrictXamlCompilation>true</MauiStrictXamlCompilation>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nThis flags **all** uncompiled bindings as warnings across the project.\n\n### Key rules to remember\n\n| Scenario | What to do |\n|---|---|\n| Bindings inside a `DataTemplate` | Add `x:DataType` on the template's root element |\n| Need to opt out for one binding | Use `x:DataType=\"x:Null\"` on that element |\n| BindingContext set in code-behind | `x:DataType` doesn't change that — it only tells the compiler what type to expect |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fc8160b3-3fc5-4ab0-8361-0f7b760a7bfe","outputTokens":627,"requestId":"3C34:1F8B8F:D4BA31:1085D48:6A0128C0"},"id":"f7e1b838-8c95-406f-b0df-ba0fc75b2289","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:54:38.526Z","parentId":"a70461b1-6d5a-42f4-b671-5bddeef858bf"}
